Comment:
This was a very painful loss. I've played this young man a few times before, but this was the first time for over a year. A couple of my previous games with him I have annotated, http://gameknot.com/annotation.pl/revenge?gm=56196
http://gameknot.com/annotation.pl/chester7vpenyffordd2wirral-league?gm=49458
This was the first surprise. In previous games he had defended with the King's Indian Defence.

The usual reply to the Dutch Defence.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dutch_Defence#White_continuations
Look a bit like he wants to head into a King's Indian formation where f7-f5 has already be played.
This is also a common move for white at some stage, against the Dutch Defence.
Black completes his fianchetto.
I want to play e2-e4.
he stops it - at least for now.
I threaten e2-e4 again.
Another common move for black in this variation.
So I play it.
He castles.
Not Nf6?? of course, breaking the protection of the pawn on e4 with my bishop. Now my plan is to play 0-0 and e4-e5, if he lets me.
Another reasonable move, blunting my Bg2 a little, so instance if I take on f5 he can take back with his Bc8 which he couldn't before.
So I continue with my plan.

I can't see this move in my databases, and I think it is a mistake to allow e4-e5, although in my databases I have come across two games where black allows e4-e5. The Gameknot game frodan (1760) vs. peacemaker (1704) continued with 8....Bc8-d7 and white continued with 9. f4 and then black played fxe4. This game ended in a draw. Trindade Rui Jorge Rodrigues (2063) vs. Costa Joao Guerra (2082) continued with 8....Na6 and once again white didn't advance and black eventually won.
So I play it.
He takes.
I take back.
Danny typically advances. My e pawn is now attacked twice.
